FINDINGS: There has been an interval increase in the overall extent and  enhancement of the diffuse pontine tumor. It measures approximately 3  .8 cm AP x 6.0 cm TV x 6.0 cm SI compared to 3.3 cm AP x 4.8 cm TV x  5.2 cm SI on the prior exam. Scattered foci of susceptibility artifact  within the tumor are consistent with small foci of intratumoral  hemorrhage and less likely mineralization. The tumor extends exophytically into the prepontine cistern  and protrudes posteriorly into the fourth ventricle.  There is increased mass effect on the fourth ventricle. Superiorly, it  extends to the middle cerebral peduncles, left greater than right.  Inferiorly, the tumor extends to the upper medulla. Posteriorly, it  extends into the middle cerebellar peduncles. There is increased  extension into the cerebral and cerebellar peduncles since the prior  study, and right cerebellar hemisphere now. On the post contrast images, there is increased enhancement of  the dorsal portions of the tumor. The lateral and third ventricles  have increased in size since the prior study. On diffusion weighted  imaging there are no areas of restricted diffusion. Incidental note  is made of a small pineal cyst.    There is bilateral maxillary sinus mucosal thickening, which almost completely occupies these sinuses as well as mucosal thickening completely filling the right sphenoid sinus; these findings have increased since the prior exam.    IMPRESSION: Interval increase in the extent and enhancement of the pontine glioma as described. Interval increase in paranasal sinus disease.

column108: six-year-old boy with a diffuse pontine glioma which was diagnosed in October 2006 when he was 4 years old. He had been previously healthy until he presented with ataxia, tripping while walking, frequent falling and facial asymmetry. Magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) revealed a pontine lesion. He was treated with 6 weeks of radiation therapy and chemotherapy.  He responded well and in January 2007. However, in May 2007 he had progression by MRI and so was started on second therapeutic regimen with Avastin and Irinotecan. He subsequently had progression on MRI in November and his chemotherapy regimen was changed. He received one dose of Tensirolomus however he had a severe allergic reaction and so began Temozolimide on December 26, 2007.  Again Edwin has had progressive symptoms and an MRI on January 5, 2008 confirmed disease progression for which he received Temozolomide from February 4 to 8. On February 27 another MRI showed findings consistent with tumor progression, particularly within the brain stem, the right temporal lobe, and the left thalamus as well as  worsening hydrocephalus and trans ependymal flow of CSF. This, as well as condition and prognosis, was discussed with his parents. It was decided not to give any further therapy that would require hospitalization, to discontinue all tubes or machines, and not to resuscitate in event of an arrest. He was discharged to hospice services on Ativan and morphine.  While in hospice on Saturday March 15 at approximately 10 a.m. began to have labored breathing and passed away.

column147: MRI OF THE BRAIN 9/6/00    HISTORY:  Patient is a five year old female with history of pontine glioma, x-ray and thalidomide therapy.     TECHNIQUE:  MR of the brain was performed using sagittal T1, sagittal T2, axial T2 and FLAIR, echo planar diffusion imaging, perfusion imaging, and MR spectroscopy. Post-Gadolinium axial and coronal T1 weighted images were obtained through the brain.    MR spectroscopy was performed by placing the voxel over the area of signal abnormality in the pons, which included part of the anterior right cerebellum. This MR spectroscopy dictation has been dictated as a separate order number.    FINDINGS:  The current exam is compared with previous study of 7/5/00. Compared with this previous study, there is now increased T2 signal identified in the right pons inferiorly. Dimensions of the signal abnormality measured on T2 weighted images are 1.1 cm (AP) x 1.0 cm (transverse), and 1.2 cm in the craniocaudal dimension. This definitely represents a change compared with previous study. Following Gadolinium administration, there is enhancement of a slightly exophytic component, which projects into the prepontine cistern adjacent to the right vertebral artery. There are no other areas of signal abnormality in the brain and there are no other areas of abnormal enhancement.     There is probably increased diffusion in the tumor.  MR spectroscopy was performed by placing the voxel over the area of pontine signal abnormality which included some of the anterior right cerebellar parenchyma. Previously identified was increased T2 signal in the left mastoid antral air cells. This signal abnormality in the left mastoid air cells is more pronounced today and more confluent.    IMPRESSION:    1) Increased signal abnormality in the right pons compared with the previous study. There is some enhancement of a slightly exophytic in the prepontine cistern near the right vertebral artery.   2) Left mastoid fluid signal.

column220: technically progressed on 10/6/00, but didn't start treatment until after this MRI - was watching    MR OF THE BRAIN, 10/6/00    HISTORY:  This is a 6-year-old female with history of brain stem glioma.  Has received x-ray therapy and is on thalidomide therapy.  The oncologist reports that the x-ray therapy was performed prior to the most recent last scan of 9/6/00.    TECHNIQUE:  MR of the brain was performed using sagittal T1, axial T2 and FLAIR, sagittal T2, and post-gadolinium sagittal and axial images through the brain.  High-resolution axial images were obtained using 3 mm slice thickness with a 1 mm skip between sections.    FINDINGS:  The current exam is compared with the most recent prior MR of 9/6/00.  There has been considerable change in the appearance of the brain stem when compared to that prior study.  Today, there is more signal abnormality identified within the lower pons and upper medulla, particularly on the right.  There is signal abnormality within the right pons at the level of the right middle cerebellar peduncle extending caudad to the upper medulla.  Again, there is a slightly exophytic component of the tumor extending near the right vertebral artery.  The amount of exophytic tumor appears increased on T2-weighted images relative to the September 6, 2000 study.  Also on the conventional images, there is slightly greater mass effect on the right aspect of the fourth ventricle.  The lateral and third ventricles are slightly larger.  Today, the T2 signal abnormality in the brainstem measures 4.0 cm. (CC) x 1.8 cm (AP) x 2.5 cm (TV) in greatest dimension.    Following administration of gadolinium, there is increased enhancement of the brainstem in the area of the T2 signal abnormality and increased tumor identified in the right prepontine cistern.  Also, there is new enhancement in the upper right medulla and right aspect of the pons which was not present on the prior study.      IMPRESSION:  1) Findings suggest lateral tumor growth with increased exophytic tumor in the right prepontine cistern.   There is increased enhancement suggesting progression of tumor.   2) The left mastoid air cells are fluid-filled as they were on the 9/6/00 study.  3) The pontine portion of the tumor is exhibiting slight increased mass effect with some compression of the right aspect of the fourth ventricle inferiorly with minimal increase in the lateral ventricular size.

column24: Specimen #1, labeled "Thalamic mass" (including 1FSA, 1SMA):    	-  Poorly differentiated malignant neoplasm most consistent with GLIOBLASTOMA (W.H.O. Grade IV/IV; ICD-0 9440/3).  See Note.    Specimen #2, labeled "More thalamic mass":    	-  Poorly differentiated malignant neoplasm most consistent with GLIOBLASTOMA (W.H.O. Grade IV/IV; ICD-0 9440/3).  See Note.    Specimen #3, labeled "Canister suction of thalamic tumor contents":    	-  Poorly differentiated malignant neoplasm most consistent with GLIOBLASTOMA (W.H.O. Grade IV/IV; ICD-0 9440/3).  See Note.    COMMENT:  This anaplastic and very mitotically active infiltrating lesion is focally, but clearly, immunoreactive for GFAP.  What is unusual for glioma is cell size, considerably larger than is typical, with the degree of nuclear molding.  These features are more consistent with high grade ("anaplastic") neuronal tumor or PNET, but synaptophysin staining is negative, and GFAP is positive. Olig2 is distinctly positive, but I have no experience with this antibody."    INTERPRETATION:  Cytogenetic analysis reveals thirteen mitotic cells from 7-8 day adherent cultures of this brain tumor specimen are characterized by near-triploidy, with numerical and structural abnormalities.  Two cells are polyploids of the original clone.  Five cells contained an apparently normal karyotype, with no evidence of clinically significant numerical or structural chromosome abnormalities.    The i(17q) is commonly associated with medulloblastoma/PNET of the CNS.    Update:  Per Dr. Folkerth the pathology is most consistent with glioblastoma.  While i(17q) is highly associated with medulloblastoma it is not an uncommon finding in other brain tumors, especially when a complex karyotype is present, such as glioblastoma."
column25: BRAIN: There is a large, rounded, mass lesion centered in the right thalamus,  measuring 4.0 cm (TV) x 5.3 cm (AP) x 40 cm (SI).  Susceptability is seen throughout the lesion and the heterogenous T1 and T2  signal intensity indicates hemorrage in various stages of evolution. T2  prolongation extends inferiorly into the left midbrain and inferolaterally  around the temporal horn. Although there are pockets of restricted diffusion  within this lesion, the lesion is hemorrhagic; there is minimal restricted  diffusion along the margins of the lesion. After contrast was given, there is a  thick linear focus of enhancement that can be followed from the lateral  posterior aspect of the lesion superiorly medially.    The lesion causes compression and shift of the midbrain to the left and the  right basal ganglia anteriorly. The internal cerebral veins and other veins are  displaced by the lesion. Branches of the right posterior cerebral artery are  displaced. There is overall mass effect on the brainstem which is as a result  located more anteriorly, and the cerebellar tonsils come up to the foramen  magnum. There is compression on the body and atria of the right lateral  ventricle and third ventricle with approximately 8 mm right to left midline  shift. There is asymmetric dilation of the anterior and temporal horns of the  right lateral ventricle with intraventricular hemorrhage layering in the  occipital horns of the bilateral lateral ventricles, greater on the right. A  ventricular catheter is in place via a left frontal approach with the tip in  the anterior horn of the left lateral ventricle.    MRA: The right middle cerebral artery is inferior and lateral to the lesion and  the right posterior cerebral artery is displaced slightly inferiorly. On the  MRA, all vessels of the circle of Willis arepatent with normal contour and no  evidence of occlusion or encasement . No aneurysm is indentified. There is no  evidence that un underlying AVM exists.

column24: NOTES:  .  The histologic features, GFAP-positivity, mitoses, and focally high MIB-1 proliferative index (13%) seen in specimen #5 are consistent with an ANAPLASTIC ASTROCYTOMA. Dr. Anthony has reviewed the case and is of the opinion that this tumor is best classified as a malignant astrocytoma.

IMPRESSION:  1. Increase in overall size of the pontine lesion. column24: NOTES:  This neoplasm is poorly-differentiated, with the only evidence of specific differentiation being the presence of processes at the light and electron microscopic level and faint focal immunoreactivity for GFAP, findings which support a tumor of glial (or astrocytic) differentiation.  The presence of frequent mitoses and extremely high cellularity and nuclear atypia are findings that support a malignant (high) grade.    The studies do not support the possibilities of primary or metastatic sarcoma, germ cell tumor, or atypical teratoid/rhabdoid tumor. The case has been reviewed by Dr. Harry Kozakewich, who agrees that this most likely represents a tumor of neuroglial origin.

Diffuse cerebral edema with flattening of gyri and optic chiasm and       fullness in area of left uncinate process and left orbitofrontal       cortex.          Numerous intraparenchymal blood vessels with organizing thrombus.          Healed surgical wound in right parietal scalp/cranium with surgical       track, level of right thalamus.   .        Intraventricular shunt in place (through right middle frontal gyrus):              Focal chronic ependymitis (secondary to shunt).              No evidence of herniation.          Status-post cerebral radiation/chemotherapy:            -  diffuse white matter rarefaction and edema;          -  scattered macrophages throughout white matter;           -  focal, periventricular white matter cavitation (particularly            prominent adjacent to the posterior horns of the lateral            ventricles);          -  minimal neuronal loss in hippocampus;          -  thickened intraparenchymal blood vessels. column24: .  Specimens #1, labeled "Intraventricular tumor" (including 1SMA, 1FSA);            #2, labeled "CUSA specimen";            #3, labeled "Brain tumor":      -  MALIGNANT ASTROCYTIC NEOPLASM (see Note).    The histologic appearance of this astrocytic tumor is somewhat unusual, particularly due to the presence of piloid-type cells, but this tumor lacks virtually all other characteristic features of a pilocytic neoplasm. The high cellularity, cellular pleomorphism, high mitotic rate with high MIB-1 index (estimated 15-20%), vascular endothelial proliferation, and scattered foci of tumor necrosis therefore suggest that this tumor is best classified as a GLIOBLASTOMA MULTIFORME (W.H.O. grade IV/IV; ICD-0 code 9440/3).

Multiple areas of heterogeneous increased abnormal T2 signal is seen throughout the brain. These areas include the right middle cerebral peduncle, the right anterior medial aspect of the temporal lobe, the right temporal horn, as well as the right cerebellum, bilateral thalamic regions, the right insular region, the right frontal horn, and the right high parietal region. Post gadolinium demonstrates variable enhancement of these areas of signal abnormality. In particular, there is nodular subependymal enhancement, and also new subtle enhancement on the surfaces of the medulla, pons, and cerebellar fissures. A new large mass demonstrating extensive enhancement is seen in the extra-axial region of the right parietal high convexity, with measurements of 3.2 AP x 3.2 TV x 2.0 SI cm. The ventricles are non-dilated.    SPINE: Sagittal views of the entire spine were obtained. Extensive almost confluent heterogeneous enhancement fills almost the entire thecal sac from the level of L1 to the sacrum. Superiorly, linear/nodular enhancement is seen surrounding the spinal cord. Two more focal discrete nodules are seen, the larger at the level of T1, and a smaller discrete nodule is also seen at the level of T10. The nodule at the level of T1 is in the left epidural space, exerts extrinsic compression on the spinal cord at this level, and extends to the left neural foramen. Also noted is spread of tumor through the right L2 neural foramen.     IMPRESSION: There has been marked interval increase of tumor seeding in both the brain and spine since prior exams from 2/06/02 and 8/25/01.

column19: There is a predominantly T2 hyperintense mass in the left parietal lobe which measures approximately 3.4 x 2.8 x 1.9 cm (anterior AP x RL x SI).  Surrounding this is extensive T2 hyperintensity in the white matter.  There is extension of similar signal into the thalamus on the left which has rounded margins.  There is also abnormal signal within the majority of the left frontal lobe.  Additionally, there is abnormal T2 hyperintensity in the medial cortex of the right frontal lobe.  There is mild midline shift at the level of the basal ganglia.  There is no hydrocephalus.  There are normal flow voids in the region of the circle of Willis included in the right anterior cerebral artery.  MRS demonstrates marked increase in the choline/NAA ratio.  There is also a large lactate peak.  Diffusion-weighted imaging demonstrates increased diffusion in the center of the mass and restricted diffusion at the periphery.  These findings are consistent with tumor.  Perfusion imaging demonstrates increased perfusion in portions of the tumor as well.    Imaging of the spine demonstrated no abnormal enhancement.    IMPRESSION:    1. High-grade tumor with the center in the left parietal lobe with extension anteriorly into the left frontal lobe and extensive surrounding T2 changes.  There is also abnormal signal in the medial right frontal cortex.  This is most consistent with a high-grade glial tumor, likely gliomatosis cerebri.  2. No hydrocephalus.  3. No evidence of metastasis to the spine.
column24: FINAL DIAGNOSIS:  .  Specimens #1, labeled "Occipital tumor" (including 1FSA);            #2, labeled "Occipital tumor" (including 2FSA);            #3, labeled "Occipital tumor" (including 3FSA);            #4, labeled "Occipital tumor" (including 4FSA)            #5, labeled "Occipital tumor":      -  HIGH-GRADE (ANAPLASTIC), INFILTRATING GLIOMA with focal ependymal      differentiation.  See note.    Specimen #6, labeled "Dura":   .    -  Fragments of dura mater with adherent ANAPLASTIC GLIOMA.  See note.    Specimen #7, labeled "Tissue in suction container":      -  Fragments of ANAPLASTIC GLIOMA consistent with specimens #1-5.    NOTES:  Overall, the findings in this case are that of a diffusely infiltrative high grade glioma with heterogeneous histology.  The infiltrative nature is consistent with reported appearance on neurimaging. In some areas it has recognizable ependymal differentiation. In these areas GFAP labelling is weak, and there is NeuN labelling, which has been reported in ependymoma (Parker et.al. found NeuN labelling in 13/20 ependymal lesions and of these 9 were anaplastic ependymomas).  Although frank invasion may rarely be seen in the anaplastic ependymomas the appearance in many regions is not ependymal and is more consistent with infiltrating glial neoplasm.  Mitoses are present and the MIB-1 index is elevated.     This case was reviewed by Dr.U.DeGirolami who commented that "this is basically an ependymoma with anaplastic features, i.e. mitoses, high MIB-1, and sheetlike growth".

He presented to the Emergency Room in December 2016 with a several months of headaches.  Imaging showed increased ventricular size with stable tumor.  Shunt exploration and ventricular catheter obstruction clearance  December 25, 2016.  He did well, however, the weekend of April 6, 2017, he developed headaches and was seen in the Emergency Room. Underwent revision of the right occipital ventriculoperitoneal shunt on April 6, 2017, as well as placement of a new ventricular catheter.  He had a subsequent shunt revision on 5/21/2017 which included exchange of the proximal catheter.  This was his last revision.  He has since been followed with surveillance imaging.  Prior to his most recent hospitalization his last MRI brain was in August 28, 2021 which showed some scattered areas of enhancing nodularity within the posterior fossa which were unchanged when compared to November 2019 scan.  He was last seen by neurosurgery in September 2021 after that scan.      With regards to his most recent hospitalization, he presented on 10/5/2021 in the setting of altered mental status, left eye deviation, with left arm posturing and potentially shaking movements.  He was initially taken to an outside hospital where he underwent CT head and CTA which showed normal appearance of the ventricles and no acute hemorrhage.  During the evaluation, he developed a generalized tonic-clonic seizure for which she received Ativan 2 mg, followed by a second generalized tonic-clonic seizure for which she received a second dose of Ativan 2 mg. He was then transferred to Boston children's for further evaluation.  On transfer, he was noted to have declining mental status with evidence of decreased movement of his extremities.  He received Keppra bolus of 60 mg/kg and was intubated for airway protection.  He was subsequently started on Keppra maintenance at 1000 mg twice daily.  He underwent an MRI brain with MRA and MRV head, which showed no interval changes with no vessel occlusion or thrombus.  He had EEG monitoring which showed slowing but no evidence of seizures.  He had a shunt tap to evaluate for infection and CSF showed no pleocytosis with a negative culture.  Toxicology screen was also sent and positive for cannabinoids.  He was extubated the next day and transferred to the neurology service.  His mental status improved back to baseline.  Overall impression was that marijuana use had triggered a first-time seizure in the setting of increased susceptibility to seizures given his tumor and surgical history.

column220: Not really a progression but development of a new glioma. Radiation was administered from February 19, 1997, until March 31, 1997. Post-radiation therapy, he developed moyamoya disease and underwent bilateral pial synangiosis. An MRI/MRA on August 26, 1998, revealed an increase in the right optic tract cyst, but otherwise stability. A followup MRI May 19, 2001, showed a decrease in the size of the right temporal cystic component of the optic glioma, but worsening abnormal signal involving the right temporal lobe. At that point, he continued to be observed. In May 2002, imaging revealed a new aneurysm involving the right M1 segment, which also was observed. An MRI from February 23, 2006, revealed increase in the cerebellar lesion for which he underwent treatment with vincristine and actinomycin D. He developed significant neurotoxicity foot drop related to the vincristine and so he received single-agent actinomycin, which was completed in July 2007. End of treatment MRI scan revealed near resolution of the cerebellar lesion. Ongoing interval MRIs have shown a slow increase in the enhancing area involving the right cerebellum and stable moyamoya disease. We have reviewed Michael's images at our brain tumor conferences and the consensus was in the absence of any clinical symptoms to continue with observation.

column24: GLIAL NEOPLASM WITHOUT ANAPLASTIC FEATURES. This tumor has some morphological features that are associated with pilocytic astrocytoma. column107: Daniel initially presented in July 2007 after a 5-month history of vomiting.  At that time, neuroimaging studies demonstrated a posterior fossa mass associated with obstructive hydrocephalus.  Initial interpretation of the pathology was a myxopapillary ependymoma.  Postoperatively, he did well and observation was recommended.  Daniel did well for 3 years and on routine surveillance MRI scan, he was found to have local progression.  He underwent a 2nd resection which was thought to be a gross total resection.  Pathology review at that time was thought to be a juvenile pilocytic astrocytoma.  His original pathology was also reinterpreted at that time as JPA.  Postoperatively, Daniel experienced significant ataxia, left-sided weakness, and hydrocephalus, which resulted in 2 shunts and a failed endoscopic 3rd ventriculostomy.  He also had decreased swallow and lower cranial nerve dysfunction for at least a month postoperatively.     Daniel also experienced meningitis associated with shunt malfunction.  He was noted to have facial weakness, decreased swallowing and speaking, and ataxia.  In April 2010, he was noted to have progression of disease and also spinal leptomeningeal disease.  A spinal tap at that time was also positive for abnormal cells.  He was then started on vincristine and carboplatin in April 2010 and bevacizumab was added to his protocol in December of that year and he remained on all 3 medications until March 2012.     After much deliberation, family elected to proceed with proton beam radiation therapy.  He is now in week six starting today and staying in Charlestown with his father during treatment.  Overall this has gone well with some limited fatigue.  There have been no skin changes.  He is doing massage therapy and school work with a tutor several times per week.  He hopes to return to school half days and has an aide in place.

column142: We explained to the family that despite her young age, Mia's tumor is not classic pediatric type-low grade glioma, but instead, her tumor is consistent with an adult-type tumor which is typified by the presence of an IDH1/2 mutation. In general, IDH mutation is associated with better outcome in adult brain tumor compared to IDH-wildtype glioma. However, despite the better prognosis and the low-grade histology, these tumors have the tendency to continue growing. In addition, when these tumor recur with time, they are known to transform into a more malignant type cancer with poor eventual outcome.    Taking these into consideration, there is good data in the adult literature that a maximal safe surgery upfront can lead to improved outcome long-term, both in terms of disease control and overall survival. As such, for Mia, given the significant residual disease that is present, our recommendation would be to proceed with maximal safe surgery in the near future. This would also allow us to have a better evaluation of the tumor tissue, to confirm the low-grade histology and decrease the likelihood of sampling error from the initial biopsy. She was therefore referred to Dr. Baird at Boston Children's Hospital, who has seen and evaluated her - and agree with the recommendation to proceed to surgery.

I have reviewed the MRI scan, and agree with the radiology report that there are new areas of enhancement associated with the left temporal tumor region.    These findings are concerning for progressive tumor, as well as possibly malignant transformation. We reviewed these findings with Mia and her mom, who noted understanding.     Our consensus recommendation is for Mia to undergo a maximal safe surgical resection, to determine the etiology of these changes we see on the MRI scan. I have discussed these recommendations with her neurosurgeon, who agreed with the plan. We will obtain a functional MRI in the next week for surgical planning.

column19: Molly initially started having headaches in January 2020 at which time they were occurring daily and varied in intensity.  There were migrainous features with dizziness, as well as light and sound sensitivity, and pounding quality.  She was initially treated with low-dose amitriptyline as well as riboflavin and magnesium, and Imitrex prescribed for rescue.  As part of her work-up, she underwent an MRI of the brain at an outside hospital on 2/4/2020 and then had a repeat at Boston children's on 2/9/2020.  This revealed a 'left occipital cortically based signal abnormality' felt most likely to be a low-grade neoplastic process such as a DNET or possibly a cortical malformation.  After initial neuro-oncology consultation, recommendation was for surveillance imaging every 3 months.    Back in May 2020, headaches appeared less severe though still daily with spikes every other week.  I recommended increasing her amitriptyline at the time to 37.5 mg at bedtime.  After that visit, mother had reached out to consider switching from amitriptyline to Zoloft for management of anxiety, as this was felt to be a likely trigger.  I made recommendations to taper off the amitriptyline and her pediatrician started her on Zoloft titrated to 50 mg daily.  Over time, Molly reported improvement in her headache frequency and severity.  She did require Imitrex for rescue a couple of times, with relief provided.  Molly discontinued her Zoloft around August 2021 in the setting of a gastrointestinal illness and did not resume it since then.         In August 2021 review of her imaging revealed that there has been slow changes over the preceding year and small foci of more pronounced signal.  In that setting, she was referred to neurosurgery for consultation, and after discussion the family opted to attempt tumor resection.  She had an fMRI on 9/21/2021 in anticipation of her surgery and underwent tumor resection on 10/26/2021.

column107: I saw her on December 21, 2021 in the setting of recurrence and worsening of headaches after surgery, which have intensified over the preceding 2 weeks.  Molly described multifocal headaches, pressure-like to pounding in nature, with intense light and sound sensitivity as well as sensitivity to smells.  There was some report of nausea but no vomiting.  These had increased in frequency to almost daily, and were severe enough to require leaving school a number of times.  Review of headache hygiene was notable for snacking throughout the day, excess screen time, and increased stress related to school.  I discussed restarting a daily preventive for her headaches and the family opted to start amitriptyline.  This was started at 12.5 mg nightly for a week and then increased to 25 mg nightly.         After my visit in February 2022, I recommended increasing the amitriptyline further to 35 mg at bedtime due to ongoing headaches of similar frequency elevated decreased severity.  I also discussed consideration of birth control method given menses associated migraines.  In the setting of some ongoing difficulties with attention and memory, I referred her to neuropsychology for an evaluation.  I saw her in follow-up last in May 2022 at which time she was doing better on the 35 mg of the amitriptyline, both with reduced frequency and severity.  She had also been started on an oral contraceptive and felt this was helpful.  She was seeing a therapist through her school but not in the outpatient setting.  She had also had some testing through school where she met some of the criteria though not all for ADHD, and was receiving accommodations through a 504 plan.  I did not make any medication changes at that time.         I last saw her in November 2022 at which time headaches were stable and I made no changes to her amitriptyline dose.  Molly had most recent MRI of the brain on 12/12/2022 which showed stable appearance of the T2 prolongation surrounding the left posterior temporal resection cavity with no new T2 prolongation or enhancement. Overall, headaches remain well controlled on the amitriptyline at 35 mg at bedtime.  She does report no recent migrainous headaches that she gets less severe tension type headaches a few times a week.  These are bifrontal and more pressure-like without any significant light or sound sensitivity nor any nausea or vomiting.  These usually improve on their own after 30 minutes, or improved with Tylenol or Motrin.  She has not needed the rescue sumatriptan.  She is currently in 11th grade with a 504 plan in place and feels this has been helpful.  Her pediatrician had prescribed Adderall, but she never started it and has not felt she needs it.  She has continued on her oral contraceptive.  She denies any concerns about sleep.  She does endorse skipping breakfast and not eating until later in the afternoon.  Her hydration has not been as robust at this previously.  She has been more physically active, working out 2-3 times a week.  She still endorses excessive screen time.  She denies any concerns about mood or significant anxiety.         Separately, she reports episodes of her knees becoming red hot and swollen and feeling like they are burning, usually lasting a few minutes.  In addition, she has similar bright red and hot sensation in her knuckles and ankles, though not with the associated burning sensation.  She was previously diagnosed with Raynaud's because of her toes turning blue and pale, but this is different.  Her primary care doctor sent some blood work including CBC, CMP, ESR, ANA, and Lyme which were reportedly normal.  Mom had her discontinue her biotin as she was unsure whether that might be contributing.

column19: history, Connor had an uneventful birth with initial normal development.  At around 8 months of age he had some episodes of bilateral extremity extension and abdominal crunching.  He was also noted to be making less eye contact and be smiling less.  He was evaluated by neurology in Rhode Island and was diagnosed with infantile spasms.  He had brain imaging at that time (around May 2014) which revealed a left parahippocampal lesion.  He was treated with ACTH with good response.  He also began early intervention and made significant progress.  Given some persistent subclinical seizures on EEG he was subsequently started on Topamax.  This was subsequently weaned off in 2015 in the setting of improved EEGs.         In May 2018 he started developing episodes in the middle of the night where he would sit up and have right eye deviation and subtle tremors.  He was evaluated with an ambulatory EEG at that time which showed seizures arising from the left frontotemporal region and sometimes secondarily generalizing.  In that setting he was started on Trileptal which was titrated to 6 mL twice daily.  He had no further seizures. In terms of the left parahippocampal lesion, this was felt to represent likely a low-grade lesion such as a DNET versus cortical dysplasia, and was followed with serial imaging initially.         I saw Connor for an initial consult on 7/13/2021.  At that time he was seizure-free on Trileptal.  Review of his imaging noted some growth of a cystic portion of the left hippocampal lesion a few years prior, though stability over the recent 2 years.  I had reviewed the differential diagnosis at that time including a low-grade tumor such as a DNET or low-grade glioma versus a cortical dysplasia.  I had recommended repeat MRI brain and spine with plan to review his case at our multidisciplinary tumor board.  Recommendation after tumor board review was for neurosurgical consultation.  His MRI brain and spine done on 8/7/2021 revealed both new enhancing nodular components and increasing size of the cystic component of the left hippocampal lesion.

She was subsequently monitored with serial MRI scans and there was interval enlargement in the lesion in 2019. She had a consultation with Dr. Baird in Neurosurgery at Boston Children s Hospital as well as review at the Boston Children s/Dana-Farber neuro-oncology tumor board, who felt that surgical resection was appropriate.

column108: With regards to her headaches, these have been ongoing for several years, but worsened in frequency and intensity and started having associated focal sensory symptoms which prompted her work-up and diagnosis.  The patient reports that headaches typically occur around her menses.  They are often holocephalic and pressure-like but can be sharper or more throbbing in nature.  They are often associated with light and sound sensitivity as well as nausea and sometimes vomiting with the more severe ones.  There is typically no aura or associated dizziness.  Headaches can occur in the morning but sometimes also later in the day.  There are no positional aspects to the headaches.  With regards to the associated sensory symptoms, these only occur with a few of her headaches.  She reports that since her surgery, she typically has been having about a handful of headaches monthly.  However, in December 2021 she counted at least 10 headaches.  She had not had recurrence of the associated focal sensory symptoms until late November when she describes numbness in her hand and wrist that then spread to involve her arm and half of her face including her tongue.  The sensory symptoms lasted about an hour and resolved but the headache persisted until the next morning despite taking Motrin.  She had a similar headache with left hemisensory symptoms on November 30, 2021 and then again early in December 2021.  Only triggers that she can identify include possibly dehydration or stress.

He has two seizure types.  Seizure number one they call the quick episode. These have been going on since he was first diagnosed. He will have a sense of deja vu, seem a little bit off but be able to maintain some responsiveness. These happen nearly daily and are brief. Seizure semiology type 2 has only been seen over the last three months. These actually started while he was admitted for what sounds like a phase 1 after reducing medications. column19: Brianna first presented at age 18 months with precocious puberty, characterized by axillary and inguinal adrenache as well as telarche. She was seen at Joe DiMaggio Children s Hospital in Hollywood, FL. She initial evaluations included primary care, Endocrinology, Genetics, Nutrition, and ORL. Her precocious puberty was ultimately unexplained and medically attributed to obesity.     She then developed progressive symptoms of dizziness, intermittent emesis, headaches and nystagmus. These symptoms waxed and waned over a period of years and lead to further evaluations by multiple subspecialists, including Hematology/Oncology. Ultimately, ORL was concerned for obstructive sleep apnea and performed a flexible laryngoscopy as well as surgical removal of the adenoids. This lead to a diagnosis of velopharyngeal insufficiency. Throughout this time, Brianna did not have neuroimaging.     Starting October 2017, Brianna s symptoms worsened with increasing headaches. She also had vocal cord changes which were attributed to left vocal cord paralysis. Her headaches were attributed to obesity and sleep apnea. On April 9, 2018, she presented to the Joe DiMaggio ED with a 2 day history of acute worsening of headache and emesis. Imaging at that time demonstrated a posterior fossa mass.
column24: ganglioglioma with a BRAF V600E mutation
column46: After discharge from LeBonheur, Brianna returned to Florida where she steadily declined in function. Specifically, she became more drowsy, had difficulty handling secretions, headaches and had worsening vocal function. During this time, she was initially seen by Dr. Rivkin and Dr Goumnerova in clinic for a second opinion in late June. She returned home with steadily worsening symptoms. She was seen multiple times by local providers and was admitted to the hospital for dehydration. Ultimately, her doctors performed an MRI on 7/3 that demonstrated a trapped fourth ventricle.      She then returned to Boston for a stereotactic-guided placement of a catheter in the trapped fourth ventricle on July 9 with Dr Goumnerova. Since then, she has steadily felt better. Her speech has significantly improved since the symptoms.     Due to presence of BRAV V600E in her tumor, she was started on vemurafenib 10/3/19 and completed vemurafenib in 12/2020.

column19: Adanya presented in July 2018 at age 17 with 3 month h/o worsening headaches. She had a h/o chronic headaches dating back as far at 2015 that tended to be band-like in quality across her forehead. Three months ago, the character of the hedaches changed significantly to that of a micraine like quality with stabbing sensation, blurry vision, and occasional tingling and neuralgias in her limbs. On several occasional, she also had associated emesis preceded by a prodrome of washed out look on her face, abdominal cramping, and left foot drag. She was seen by 2 different neurologists in the intervening time and treated for complicated migraine. No head imaging was done and EEG was reportedly normal.      On July 4, she woke up with an intense headache and nausea. Given the severity of the symptoms, she went to the Exeter Hospital ED. Labs were unremarkable. MRI of the brain showed a right temporal lobe mass with significant vasogenic edema and mild mid-line shift with mild hydrocephalus, prompting transfer to BCH.    After arrival at BCH, Neurosurgery was consulted and she was started on dexamethasone. She had a repeat MRI of the brain and spine.

Arakel presented acutely on 3/12/18 when a large piece of heavy metal (2ft x 1 cm L-shaped 10-15lb piece of steel) hit him in the head by accident whilst in shop class.  It struck the right posterior head and neck. He had no loss of consciousness but reported immediate onset headaches. He then developed slurred speech, facial weakness on one side and vomiting. He was taken to UMass and an MRI was performed under the recommendation of Neurology that revealed diffuse leptomeningeal enhancement of uncertain significance.    Arakel was extensively investigated and treated for presumed meningitis. He was noted to have an elevated CSF protein content on 2 respective samples on 3/14/18 and 3/16/18. In addition to antibiotics, he was managed with verapamil as complicated migraine.  Treated also with Keppra, Toradol, Morphine, Zofran, Reglan, Benadryl, Tylenol, Pepcid per the discharge summary.  His neurological symptoms and signs were noted to improve over the subsequent weeks (as per parents).    In light of the complicated nature of Arakel's presentation and abnormalities on MRI and CSF, the family sort a second opinion form Dr Benson (Neuro-Immunologist). Dr Benson discussed malignancy as one of the possibilities for this presentation and Arakel's case was discussed at Neuro-Oncology Multidisciplinary Conference on 4/26/18.

llian presented at age 16 years with 8 month history of worsening headaches, thought be be migraines. The headache acutely worsened a few weeks prior to her presentation with associated episodes of emesis. She went to an OSH, where CT brain showed a ~6 cm diameter posterior fossa tumor with hydrocephalus, for which she was sent to BCH ED. Initial Brain and spine MRIs showed a heterogeneous large posterior fossa mass with minimal enhancement, coarse calcifications and multiple tumoral cysts. The mass was noted to extend through the foramen of Magendie inferiorly and foramina of Luschka on the left. There was also crowding at the foramen magnum with inferior herniation of the cerebral tonsils in the setting of significant obstructive hydrocephalus with periventricular edema. Spinal MRI did not show any evidence of intracranial leptomeningeal or intraspinal spinal drop metastasis. She was admitted to the MSICU, steroids were initiated with significant improvement of symptoms.

column19: John developed staring episodes starting in May which the parents realized in retrospect were likely absence seizures. The very first episode the parents noted occurred while he was standing in the shower. His mother was getting ready to take his sister to school and realized he was still in the shower. When she went to check on him, he did not respond so she went to look in on him and found him standing in the shower and just staring down and complete unaware. She said his name several times and it was probably about 2 min before he finally responded and at that point he seemed completely disoriented. He had several more staring episodes thereafter. Another event occurred while at a friend s house and witnessed by the friend s mother. He had just finished eating and then began stating straight ahead, unresponsive for about 45 seconds. He came to but was unable to answer questions fully for about 2-3 minutes. A similar episode occurred again later in the week about 10 minutes after waking and during which he was talking with his parents. That time, however, they noted his eyes began to move in all directions while his L hand began to shake and he began to wring his hands. This event lasted 2-3 minutes. He had difficulty answering questions for about 15 min therafter. John does not remember much before or after these events. He underwent video EEG that showed left temporal slowing and sharp waves along with a 1.5 minute left temporal lobe seizure w/o a clear clinical correlate.

column19: Breslyn presented at the age of 5 years in July 2017 with 1-2 year history of chronic headaches which were largely improved with OTC medication. About a week prior to presentation, Breslyn developed emesis with her headaches without associated vision changes, weakness/numbness, gait abnormalities, or seizures. She was evaluated by her PMD who ordered an urgent outpatient MRI which revealed a new mass. She was then directed to BCH ED for further care. She was admitted to the Neurosurgery service where she underwent full brain/spine imaging which showed a third ventricular mass with obstructive hydrocephalus. MRI highlighted two distinct nodules which appeared separate though in close proximity to the primary tumor and were therefore concerning for intracranial dissemination. No other evidence of intracranial or intrathecal CSF dissemination. Upon admission, Breslyn was started on Decadron. column19: developed seizures around 1-1.5 years of age.  Trenton's seizures tending to be of two types. Trentons'  most recent seizure was that of the first type and last occurred in Feb 2017. His seizures had been well controlled for some time on carbamazepine monotherapy. At 10 months, he was feeding from a bottle, then afterwards had an episode in which his eyes were half closed and his body became "floppy" for five to ten seconds.  After this episode, he was quiet for five to ten minutes and then went back to playing.  He was then seen in the Winchester ED where he was observed and then sent home. Following this event, we saw him in clinic on 3/25/15 and he had a routine EEG (4/14/15) that was normal in the awake and sleep states.         Since around late February 2016, Lucas has had episodes of behavioral arrest, with staring, drooling, right arm extension, and sometimes falling. Afterwards, he has decreased activity for around 15-20 minutes. Given concern for seizure activity, he underwent a routine EEG on 3/18/16, which was normal while awake and asleep. These episodes occurred 2-3 times per week. He was started on Keppra 160mg BID (~36mg/kg/day) as a diagnostic and therapeutic trial, which appeared to decrease his overall seizure frequency to around 1-2 per week. In particular, he has had fewer of his "big" seizures, in which he stops and stares or smiles, then either falls to the ground or stays standing, sometimes with dragging of the right side of his body, with eyes open, sometimes picking at his clothes with his left hand. He still has his "small" seizures with staring for 10-15 seconds. Since starting the Keppra, however, he has had behavioral side effects, with impulsivity, which were not noted before.
